                <article data-uuid="b5b9c332ef0344e18e824c0d33a5c51a">
                    <h3 class="mod" data-uuid="22b80936bbf9450f8715823374feeb01">Citizenship and the Constitution, 1787–1990</h3>
                    <p class="mod" data-uuid="6b6d27b25c1b453484a434b23f6b3730">Our nation’s Founders struggled with how best to
                        prevent government abuse of power. Their answer was a Constitution that
                        described the government, its powers, and the limits on it. The first ten amendments of their Constitution—the
                        Bill of Rights—guaranteed the rights of citizens. In return for
                        these precious rights, U.S. citizens have a responsibility to actively
                        participate in government.</p>
                </article>
